<br>
I can't speak to how officers are chosen since, well, it's not very often and I've not been around to see it. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
None of the officers have unique duties that I am aware of, Kelandria is the nominal guild leader but exerts no more influence (that I've felt) outside of the other officers that I have seen.  None has a title of any kind and in fact there is never really any talk of &quot;the officers&quot; on the mailing list or in /gu.<br>
<br>
I would consider Amici a fairly small guild, actually, or mid-sized, but certainly not a large one by any stretch of the imagination.  Yet dispite this, we're able to regularly kill mobs like Gorenaire, Trakanon, Severilius (when the bastage is up) and just accomplished our first Derakor the Vindicator kill.  We also regularly clear Halls of Testing in Temple of Veeshan with as little as 18 (normally have more than this) people (and have raided there successfully with as few as 11).<br>
<br>
This is a tough one, really.  As a whole, the goals of everyone in Amici are so amazingly in line that the guild has a whole seems to move in the same direction regardless of the actions of the officers.  In my opinion (and my guildmates may or may not agree with me), the &quot;guild leadership&quot; are not so much the officers, but rather those members with the initiative to plan and organize events.  The officers facilitate that by making those decsions that are politically sensitive and that none of the rest of us want to deal with anyway.  The members as a whole vote on the admission of new members to the ranks.<br>
<br>
Amici does not have a guild message board such as EZBoard, but relies on a private mailing list to communicate with the other members while not in game.  This is a big switch from the last guild I was in where EZboard was used.  The mailing list is quite popular and an enjoyable forum in which to communicate when not otherwise able to do so (read: when not actually able to be in game).<br>
<br>
